VJohn Calvin (French: Jean Calvin, born Jehan Cauvin: 10 July 1509\ufffd\u2013 27 May 1564) was an influential French theologian and pastor during the Protestant Reformation.
p2
aVHe was a principal figure in the development of the system of Christian theology later called Calvinism.
p3
aVOriginally trained as a humanist lawyer, he broke from the Roman Catholic Church around 1530.
p4
aVAfter religious tensions provoked a violent uprising against Protestants in France, Calvin fled to Basel, Switzerland, where he published the first edition of his seminal work The Institutes of the Christian Religion in 1536.
p5
aVIn that year, Calvin was recruited by William Farel to help reform the church in Geneva.
p6
aVThe city council resisted the implementation of Calvin's and Farel's ideas, and both men were expelled.
p7
aVAt the invitation of Martin Bucer, Calvin proceeded to Strasbourg, where he became the minister of a church of French refugees.
p8
aVHe continued to support the reform movement in Geneva, and was eventually invited back to lead its church.
p9
aVFollowing his return, Calvin introduced new forms of church government and liturgy, despite the opposition of several powerful families in the city who tried to curb his authority.
p10
aVDuring this period, Michael Servetus, a Spaniard known for his heretical views, arrived in Geneva.
p11
aVHe was denounced by Calvin and executed by the city council.
p12
aVFollowing an influx of supportive refugees and new elections to the city council, Calvin's opponents were forced out.
p13
aVCalvin spent his final years promoting the Reformation both in Geneva and throughout Europe.
p14
aVCalvin was a tireless polemic and apologetic writer who generated much controversy.
p15
aVHe also exchanged cordial and supportive letters with many reformers, including Philipp Melanchthon and Heinrich Bullinger.
p16
aVIn addition to the Institutes, he wrote commentaries on most books of the Bible, as well as theological treatises and confessional documents.
p17
aVHe regularly preached sermons throughout the week in Geneva.
p18
aVCalvin was influenced by the Augustinian tradition, which led him to expound the doctrine of predestination and the absolute sovereignty of God in salvation of the human soul from death and eternal damnation.
p19
aVCalvin's writing and preachings provided the seeds for the branch of theology that bears his name.
p20
aVThe Reformed and Presbyterian churches, which look to Calvin as a chief expositor of their beliefs, have spread throughout the world.
